I find the setting interesting, and you do the reader a favor by not pinching off a massive lore-dump right at the start of the story and instead interspersing pieces of worldbuilding throughout. You ever dive into a story with a fantasy setting, but it feels the need to just lay everything out right there and spoil the mystique? It feels unnatural and completely out of place. Yours doesn't do that.
It establishes an air of professionalism with the main character, informing the reader about her personality instead of straight-up telling them. In other words, it abides by the golden rule of "show don't tell."

Weaknesses I'm not so sure on. I might come up with a few as I read more, but for now nothing comes off the top of my head.

The problem is that you just blew your load telling everyone the summary of a potential story instead of just writing it. Hoping people will tell you if it's good or not.
Your story sounds like melodramatic shit, but that doesn't mean if it was actually written it would be. A summary is basically taking all the intricacies of a story and turning it into a wikipedia article. It will always sound like shit. Furthermore, now everyone knows what is going to happen if you actually do end up writing this, people know the resolution and therefore aren't as invested.
There's a difference between a writing prompt or a pitch and a summary. One is:
>So Anon's in college and he meets this seriously tall, buff awoo who has serious social anxiety. Sound good?
The other is:
>Anon, after leaving a trouble home manages to get into college after a lot of hard work. He still has nightmares about his upbringing, but it won't be until the end that the reader knows the origins. He befriends muscular wolf girl thrice his size, who has serious social anxiety problems and has to take medication to even function. It turns out that she too, had a troubled upbringing and the two bond over their shared experience as Anon gets Awoo to open up to other people while she helps him get over his trauma. During this part of the story I would write in intricate detail about how she cuddles him during his nightmares and how her soft fur makes Anon feel safe and warm. Instead of doing that, I'm just gonna say she cuddled him and leave it at that. Then they get married and they both confront their abusive parents. The end.
